    "narrative_summary": "Across the corpus, Adidas shifts from being seen mainly as part of the sporting stage to becoming the author of the stage itself. In the earliest footage, the brand is present through event infrastructure and performance equipment: the official World Cup ball, national-team kits, and tournament-adjacent gear. The storytelling is largely borrowed from the spectacle of global sport, with Adidas functioning as the visual system around elite competition rather than the central narrative voice.\n\nBy the early-to-mid 2010s, Adidas starts moving into authored brand worlds. The London 2012 Team GB material reframes sponsorship as design partnership, making kit development, fabrication, and presentation part of the story. The 2014 Messi-led football film goes further: Adidas is no longer just visible on athletes or equipment, but uses product close-ups, end cards, and campaign visual language to turn competitive mentality into a branded narrative. From there, product films like Yeezy Boost and NMD intensify control over image-making through isolated hero shots, exploded construction views, and highly stylized urban environments.\n\nLater entries expand Adidas beyond performance into culture and values. The Samba video explicitly traces a football shoe's migration into fashion, collaboration, and everyday lifestyle, with trefoil apparel, product tableaux, and collab editions standing in for a broader Originals identity. The Parley piece marks another evolution: Adidas uses product imagery, recycled-material symbolism, and co-brand iconography to present itself as a platform for sustainability storytelling, not just athletic aspiration.\n\nThe newest campaign material completes the transition. In the 2024 'You Got This' spots, Adidas blends sport, emotion, and cinematic montage across football, basketball, boxing, running, and skateboarding, ending on stripped-down three-stripe logos. The brand's visual storytelling has evolved from sponsorship visibility inside major events to fully owned films that connect performance, identity, design culture, and environmental purpose.",
